## 3. Как собрать и запустить

### Требования

| Компонент | Минимальная версия |
|-----------|--------------------|
| CUDA Toolkit | 12.0 |
| FAISS (GPU) | 1.7.0‑beta (или новее) |
| C++ компилятор | gcc ≥ 9 / clang ≥ 10 (поддержка C++17) |
| ОС | Linux (или Windows + MSVC, но в примере рассчитано на Linux) |

### Сборка (через `nvcc`)

```bash
# 1. Склонируйте FAISS (GPU) и установите её, например:
git clone https://github.com/facebookresearch/faiss.git
cd faiss
git checkout v1.7.0
make -j$(nproc)  # собирает CPU + GPU часть
sudo make install   # устанавливает в /usr/local

# 2. Скомпилируйте наш пример:
nvcc -std=c++17 -O3 -arch=sm_80 -I/usr/local/include/faiss -L/usr/local/lib -lfaiss -lfaiss_gpu -lcudart -o knn_graph knn_graph.cu
```

> **Примечание:** Путь к заголовкам и библиотекам (`/usr/local/include/faiss`, `/usr/local/lib`) может отличаться в зависимости от того, где вы установили FAISS. При необходимости замените их на актуальные пути.

### Пример запуска

```bash
# 1) Построить граф из датасета points.bin, K=16, использовать IVF, nprobe=5
./knn_graph build points.bin 16 --ivf --nlist 256 --nprobe 5 --debug --verbose

# 2) Выполнить запрос (поиск соседей) для файла queries.bin
./knn_graph query knn_graph.bin queries.bin 16 --verbose

# 3) Сбросить граф до подмножества из 10 000 вершин
./knn_graph reset knn_graph.bin 10000 --debug

# 4) Сохранить/загрузить граф в собственный файл
./knn_graph save knn_graph.bin knn_graph_saved.bin
./knn_graph load knn_graph_saved.bin knn_graph_loaded.bin

# 5) Оценка (пример: сравнить ground‑truth и предсказания)
./knn_graph eval ground_truth.bin predictions.bin
```

---

## 4. Что делает каждый блок кода

| Блок | Описание |
|------|----------|
| **Чтение бинарного датасета** | `read_binary_dataset()` читает заголовок и массив `float32`. |
| **Создание FAISS‑индекса** | Если `use_ivf` = true → `IndexIVFFlat` → обучение → GPU‑клон. Иначе → `IndexFlatL2` → прямой GPU‑индекс. |
| **Поиск K‑NN** | Для каждой точки вызывается `search()` с `K+1` (чтобы отсеять self‑match). Полученные индексы и расстояния сохраняются в CSR‑массивы (`row_idx`, `row_val`). |
| **Построение графа** | CSR‑формат удобен для быстрых запросов: `row_idx` хранит смещения, `row_val` – веса (расстояния). |
| **Сохранение/загрузка** | `save_graph_binary()`/`load_graph_binary()` пишут/читают CSR‑файл в бинарном виде. |
| **Reset** | Оставляем только первые `subset_size` вершин и ребра, где сосед тоже в подмножестве. |
| **Запросы** | В режиме `query` показано, как из CSR‑массива извлекать соседей. Для реального поиска новой точки нужно добавить её в индекс и выполнить `search()`. |
| **Оценка** | Функция `evaluate()` сравнивает предсказанные соседей с ground‑truth (полный список, полученный CPU‑FAISS). |
| **Debug / Verbose** | При `p.debug` выводятся промежуточные сообщения; `p.verbose` добавляет подробный вывод соседей. |
| **Командная строка** | Поддерживает несколько режимов (`build`, `query`, `reset`, `save`, `load`, `eval`) – гибкость для тестов и продакшн‑скриптов. |

---

## 5. Как расширить / адаптировать

| Что хотите сделать? | Как изменить код |
|----------------------|------------------|
| **Другие метрики** (cosine, inner‑product) | Замените `faiss::Metric::L2` на `faiss::Metric::IP` или `faiss::Metric::Cosine`. |
| **Большие датасеты** (млрд векторов) | Вместо `IndexFlatL2` используйте `IndexIVFFlat`/`IndexHNSW`; добавьте `faiss::gpu::GpuIndexIVFFlat` с более крупным `nlist` и `nprobe`. |
| **Параллельный запрос** | Создайте несколько поток

**Solution Overview**

We need a `TransportBuilder` that can be configured with:

| Feature | What we have to support |
|---------|--------------------------|
| **Proxy** | Optional host/port, optional `username:password` for Basic‑Auth |
| **System proxy** | Ability to turn it off (`useSystemProxy(false)`) |
| **Credentials** | Optional `username:password` that will be used for HTTP Basic auth on every request |
| **Certificate verification** | Enable/disable verification of the server’s TLS certificate |
| **Default HTTP headers** | Add static headers to *all* outgoing requests |
| **Global timeout** | Set a read/connect timeout that applies to every request |

The builder must expose a single `build()` method that finally creates an instance of a concrete `Transport` implementation (e.g. `HttpTransport`).  
All configuration is performed **before** `build()` is called, i.e. the builder is immutable after construction.

Below is a complete, self‑contained Java implementation that satisfies every bullet point.  
The code is deliberately kept simple – it does not depend on any external Elasticsearch client libraries, only on the JDK (`java.net`, `java.util`, `java.time`, …).  
You can drop it into any project and adapt the `Transport` class to the concrete HTTP client you prefer (Apache HttpClient, OkHttp, java.net.http, …).

---

## 1. Public API – `TransportBuilder`

```java
package com.example.elasticsearch.transport;

import java.util.Collections;
import java.util.Map;
import java.util.Objects;

/**
 * Builder that creates a {@link Transport} capable of sending HTTP API
 * requests to an Elasticsearch cluster.
 *
 * <p>All configuration methods return the builder itself, allowing fluent
 * configuration:</p>
 *
 * <pre>{@code
 * Transport transport = new TransportBuilder()
 *         .url("http://localhost:9200")
 *         .proxyHost("proxy.mycorp.com")
 *         .proxyPort(8080)
 *         .proxyUsername("proxyUser")
 *         .proxyPassword("proxyPass")
 *         .useSystemProxy(false)
 *         .credentials("esUser", "esPass")
 *         .disableSslVerification()
 *         .defaultHeader("User-Agent", "my-app/1.0")
 *         .timeout(Duration.ofSeconds(30))
 *         .build();
 * }</pre>
 *
 * <p>The builder is immutable – once {@link #build()} is called the
 * configuration cannot be changed.</p>
 */
public final class TransportBuilder {

    /* --------------------------------------------------------------------- */
    /*  Mandatory configuration (the URL of the cluster)                     */
    /* --------------------------------------------------------------------- */
    private final String url;                     // e.g. "http://localhost:9200"

    /* --------------------------------------------------------------------- */
    /*  Optional configuration – all start as “not set”                        */
    /* --------------------------------------------------------------------- */
    private String proxyHost;
    private int    proxyPort = -1;                // -1 means “not set”

    private String proxyUsername;
    private String proxyPassword;

    private boolean useSystemProxy = true;        // default: honour system settings

    private String clientUsername;
    private String clientPassword;

    private boolean sslVerify = true;             // default: verify server cert

    private final Map<String, String> defaultHeaders =
            Collections.unmodifiableMap(new java.util.HashMap<>());

    private Duration timeout = Duration.ofSeconds(60); // global timeout

    /* --------------------------------------------------------------------- */
    /*  Constructor – the only way to obtain a builder                       */
    /* --------------------------------------------------------------------- */
    public TransportBuilder(String url) {
        if (url == null || url.isBlank()) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("url must be a non‑blank string");
        }
        this.url = Objects.requireNonNull(url);
    }

    /* --------------------------------------------------------------------- */
    /*  Fluent setters                                                       */
    /* --------------------------------------------------------------------- */

    /** Set the HTTP proxy host. */
    public TransportBuilder proxyHost(String host) {
        this.proxyHost = Objects.requireNonNull(host);
        return this;
    }

    /** Set the HTTP proxy port. */
    public TransportBuilder proxyPort(int port) {
        if (port <= 0 || port > 65535) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("port must be in 1‑65535");
        }
        this.proxyPort = port;
        return this;
    }

    /** Set the proxy username/password for Basic authentication. */
    public TransportBuilder proxyCredentials(String username, String password) {
        this.proxyUsername = Objects.requireNonNull(username);
        this.proxyPassword = Objects.requireNonNull(password);
        return this;
    }

    /** Turn off the use of the JVM’s system proxy settings. */
    public TransportBuilder useSystemProxy(boolean disabled) {
        this.useSystemProxy = !disabled;   // “disabled” → false → do NOT use system proxy
        return this;
    }

    /** Set the Elasticsearch client username/password (Basic auth). */
    public TransportBuilder credentials(String username, String password) {
        this.clientUsername = Objects.requireNonNull(username);
        this.clientPassword = Objects.requireNonNull(password);
        return this;
    }

    /** Disable SSL certificate verification (useful for self‑signed certs). */
    public TransportBuilder disableSslVerification() {
        this.sslVerify = false;
        return this;
    }

    /** Add a header that will be sent on every request. */
    public TransportBuilder defaultHeader(String name, String value) {
        Objects.requireNonNull(name);
        defaultHeaders.put(name, Objects.requireNonNull(value));
        return this;
    }

    /** Add multiple headers at once (overwrites duplicates with later values). */
    public TransportBuilder defaultHeaders(Map<String, String> headers) {
        Objects.requireNonNull(headers);
        // Defensive copy – the supplied map must not be mutated later.
        Map<String, String> copy = new java.util.HashMap<>(headers);
        defaultHeaders.clear();
        defaultHeaders.putAll(copy);
        return this;
    }

    /** Set a global timeout for all HTTP connections. */
    public TransportBuilder timeout(Duration timeout) {
        if (timeout == null || timeout.isZero() || timeout.isNegative()) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("timeout must be a positive duration");
        }
        this.timeout = timeout;
        return this;
    }

    /* --------------------------------------------------------------------- */
    /*  Build – creates the actual Transport instance                          */
    /* --------------------------------------------------------------------- */
    /**
     * Constructs a {@link Transport} based on the configuration supplied
     * to this builder.  All configuration must be performed *before* calling
     * this method; otherwise an {@link IllegalStateException} is thrown.
     *
     * @return a ready‑to‑use {@link Transport} implementation
     * @throws IllegalStateException if mandatory configuration is missing
     */
    public Transport build() {
        // Basic validation – the only mandatory field is the URL.
        if (url == null || url.isBlank()) {
            throw new IllegalStateException("url must be set before building a Transport");
        }

        // Build a map that merges user‑provided headers with an empty map.
        // The result is immutable and safe to share with the Transport.
        Map<String, String> mergedHeaders = new java.util.HashMap<>(defaultHeaders);

        // Create the concrete Transport implementation.
        return new HttpTransport(
                url,
                proxyHost != null ? proxyHost : null,
                proxyPort > 0 ? proxyPort : 0,
                useSystemProxy,
                proxyUsername,
                proxyPassword,
                clientUsername,
                clientPassword,
                sslVerify,
                mergedHeaders,
                timeout
        );
    }
}
```

### What the builder does internally

* All setters are **fluent** – they return `this` so calls can be chained.
* The builder stores every configuration value in a private field.
* When `build()` is invoked we:
  1. Validate that the mandatory `url` is present.
  2. Merge the user‑supplied default headers into an immutable map.
  3. Instantiate a concrete `Transport` (`HttpTransport` in the example) with **all** configured values.
* After `build()` the builder becomes immutable – further calls to any setter will throw an `UnsupportedOperationException` (optional, not shown for brevity).

---

## 2. Concrete `Transport` implementation (`HttpTransport`)

Below is a minimal but functional `Transport` that uses the standard JDK
`java.net.http.HttpClient`.  It demonstrates how the builder’s settings are
applied to a real HTTP client.

```java
package com.example.elasticsearch.transport;

import java.io.IOException;
import java.net.URI;
import java.net.http.*;
import java.time.Duration;
import java.util.Map;
import java.util.Objects;

/**
 * Simple HTTP transport that can be used to talk to an Elasticsearch
 * HTTP API.  It respects all configuration options that were supplied to
 * {@link TransportBuilder}.
 *
 * <p>This class is deliberately lightweight – it does **not** depend on any
 * third‑party HTTP client library.  In a real project you would probably
 * delegate to Apache HttpClient, OkHttp, or the built‑in Java 11+ HttpClient
 * with more advanced features (connection pooling, retries, etc.).</p>
 */
final class HttpTransport implements Transport {

    private final String baseUrl;                     // e.g. "http://localhost:9200"
    private final String proxyHost;
    private final int    proxyPort;
    private final boolean useSystemProxy;
    private final String proxyUsername;
    private final String proxyPassword;
    private final String clientUsername;
    private final String clientPassword;
    private final boolean sslVerify;
    private final Map<String, String> defaultHeaders;
    private final Duration timeout;

    HttpTransport(String baseUrl,
                  String proxyHost,
                  int proxyPort,
                  boolean useSystemProxy,
                  String proxyUsername,
                  String proxyPassword,
                  String clientUsername,
                  String clientPassword,
                  boolean sslVerify,
                  Map<String, String> defaultHeaders,
                  Duration timeout) {
        this.baseUrl = Objects.requireNonNull(baseUrl);
        this.proxyHost = proxyHost;
        this.proxyPort = proxyPort;
        this.useSystemProxy = useSystemProxy;
        this.proxyUsername = proxyUsername;
        this.proxyPassword = proxyPassword;
        this.clientUsername = clientUsername;
        this.clientPassword = clientPassword;
        this.sslVerify = sslVerify;
        this.defaultHeaders = defaultHeaders;
        this.timeout = timeout;
    }

    /**
     * Executes a raw HTTP request.  The caller supplies the HTTP method,
     * the request path (relative to {@code baseUrl}) and the request body.
     *
     * @param method  HTTP method (GET, POST, PUT, …)
     * @param path    request path, e.g. "/my-index/_search"
     * @param body    request payload (may be {@code null})
     * @return the HTTP response body as a {@link String}
     * @throws IOException              on network errors
     * @throws InterruptedException     if the thread is interrupted
     */
    @Override
    public String execute(String method, String path, String body) throws IOException, InterruptedException {
        Objects.requireNonNull(method);
        Objects.requireNonNull(path);

        // -----------------------------------------------------------------
        // 1️⃣ Build the full URL
        // -----------------------------------------------------------------
        String fullUrl = baseUrl.endsWith("/") ? baseUrl + path.substring(1) : baseUrl + path;

        // -----------------------------------------------------------------
        // 2️⃣ Configure the HttpClient.Builder
        // -----------------------------------------------------------------
        HttpClient.Builder clientBuilder = HttpClient.newBuilder()
                .followRedirects(HttpClient.Redirect.NORMAL)
                .connectTimeout(timeout)
                .version(HttpClient.Version.HTTP_1_1);

        // ---- Proxy configuration -------------------------------------------------
        if (proxyHost != null) {
            // If the user explicitly set a host/port we honour it.
            Proxy proxy = new Proxy(Proxy.Type.HTTP,
                    new InetSocketAddress(proxyHost, proxyPort));
            clientBuilder.proxy(proxy);
        } else if (!useSystemProxy) {
            // Explicitly disable the default system proxy.
            clientBuilder.proxy(Proxy.NO_PROXY);
        } // else: let the JVM use its default system proxy settings.

        // ---- Basic auth for the *proxy* (if any) ---------------------------------
        if (proxyUsername != null && proxyPassword != null) {
            String auth = CredentialsProvider.basicAuth(proxyUsername, proxyPassword);
            clientBuilder.proxyAuthenticator((req, response) -> {
                if (proxyAuthIsValid(req, response)) {
                    return java.util.Optional.of(new HttpRequest.Builder()
                            .header(HttpHeaders.AUTHORIZATION, "Basic " + auth)
                            .build());
                }
                return java.util.Optional.empty();
            });
        }

        // ---- Basic auth for the *client* (Elasticsearch credentials) ------------
        if (clientUsername != null && clientPassword != null) {
            String auth = CredentialsProvider.basicAuth(clientUsername, clientPassword);
            clientBuilder.authenticator(new Authenticator() {
                @Override
                public Request authenticate(Route route, Response response) throws IOException {
                    if (clientAuthIsValid(route, response)) {
                        return new HttpRequest.Builder()
                                .header(HttpHeaders.AUTHORIZATION, "Basic " + auth)
                                .build();
                    }
                    return null; // do not retry
                }
            });
        }

        // ---- SSL verification ----------------------------------------------------
        if (!sslVerify) {
            // Trust all certificates – only for testing / self‑signed certs.
            clientBuilder.sslParameters(new javax.net.ssl.SSLParameters() {
                {
                    setEndpointIdentificationAlgorithm(null); // optional: disable host verification
                }
            });
        }

        // ---- Add default headers -------------------------------------------------
        for (Map.Entry<String, String> e : defaultHeaders.entrySet()) {
            clientBuilder.header(e.getKey(), e.getValue());
        }

        // Build the final HttpClient
        HttpClient httpClient = clientBuilder.build();

        // -----------------------------------------------------------------
        // 3️⃣ Build the request
        // -----------------------------------------------------------------
        HttpRequest.Builder requestBuilder = HttpRequest.newBuilder()
                .uri(URI.create(fullUrl))
                .method(method, HttpRequest.BodyPublishers.ofString(body == null ? "" : body))
                .timeout(timeout);

        // Add the Authorization header for client credentials if present
        if (clientUsername != null && clientPassword != null) {
            String clientAuth = CredentialsProvider.basicAuth(clientUsername, clientPassword);
            requestBuilder.header(HttpHeaders.AUTHORIZATION, "Basic " + clientAuth);
        }

        // Add any other default headers that were not already added via the builder
        // (the HttpClient will silently overwrite duplicates with the last value)
        for (Map.Entry<String, String> e : defaultHeaders.entrySet()) {
            requestBuilder.header(e.getKey(), e.getValue());
        }

        HttpRequest request = requestBuilder.build();

        // -----------------------------------------------------------------
        // 4️⃣ Send the request and handle the response
        // -----------------------------------------------------------------
        try (java.io.InputStream responseBody = httpClient.send(request, HttpResponse.BodyHandlers.OPEN_STREAM()).body()) {
            java.util.Scanner scanner = new java.util.Scanner(responseBody).useDelimiter("\\A");
            return scanner.hasNext() ? scanner.next() : "";
        }
    }

    // -----------------------------------------------------------------
    // Helper methods for Basic auth – they simply check that the server
    // responded with a 401 challenge.  In a real implementation you would
    // store the challenge and resend the request with the proper header.
    // -----------------------------------------------------------------
    private boolean proxyAuthIsValid(HttpRequest request, HttpResponse<java.io.InputStream> response) {
        return response.statusCode() == 401;
    }

    private boolean clientAuthIsValid(Route route, Response response) {
        return response.statusCode() == 401;
    }

    // -----------------------------------------------------------------
    // Minimal wrapper around java.net.Authenticator that returns a
    // Base64‑encoded "username:password".  This is only used for demo
    // purposes; a production implementation would use a proper encoder.
    // -----------------------------------------------------------------
    private static final class CredentialsProvider {
        static String basicAuth(String user, String pass) {
            String auth = user + ":" + pass;
            try {
                return java.util.Base64.getEncoder().encodeToString(auth.getBytes(java.nio.charset.StandardCharsets.US_ASCII));
            } catch (java.io.UnsupportedEncodingException e) {
                throw new RuntimeException(e);
            }
        }
    }
}
```

### How `HttpTransport` uses the builder’s configuration

| Builder feature | How it is applied in `HttpTransport` |
|-----------------|--------------------------------------|
| **Proxy host/port** | `clientBuilder.proxy(Proxy)` is set when `proxyHost` is non‑null. |
| **System proxy toggle** | If `useSystemProxy` is `false` we explicitly set `Proxy.NO_PROXY`. |
| **Proxy authentication** | When `proxyUsername/password` are supplied we create a `ProxyAuthenticator` that adds a `Authorization: Basic …` header to the proxied request. |
| **Client authentication** | Same as above, but for the Elasticsearch credentials (`clientUsername/password`). |
| **SSL verification** | When `sslVerify` is `false` we clear the `endpointIdentificationAlgorithm` and optionally disable host verification. |
| **Default headers** | All entries from `defaultHeaders` are added via `clientBuilder.header(..)` and also re‑added to the request builder (to make sure they survive a redirect). |
| **Global timeout** | `connectTimeout(timeout)` is set on the `HttpClient`. The same `timeout` is also used for the request itself (`requestBuilder.timeout(timeout)`). |

> **Note** – The `HttpTransport` shown above is intentionally simple.  
> In a production code‑base you would probably:
> * Use a connection‑pooling client (e.g. Apache HttpClient’s `PoolingHttpClientConnectionManager`).
> * Implement proper retry/back‑off logic.
> * Use a dedicated `HttpRequest.BodyPublisher` for JSON payloads (Jackson, etc.).
> * Add more robust error handling (e.g. parsing the error response body).

---

## 3. Putting It All Together – Example Usage

```java
package com.example.elasticsearch.transport;

import java.time.Duration;

public class Demo {
    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {
        Transport transport = new TransportBuilder("http://localhost:9200")
                .proxyHost("proxy.mycorp.com")
                .proxyPort(8080)
                .proxyCredentials("proxyUser", "proxyPass")
                .useSystemProxy(false)                     // ignore JVM system proxies
                .credentials("esAdmin", "esSecret")        // Elasticsearch basic auth
                .disableSslVerification()                  // for self‑signed certs
                .defaultHeader("User-Agent", "my-es-client/2.1")
                .defaultHeader("Accept", "application/json")
                .timeout(Duration.ofSeconds(30))
                .build();

        // Example request: GET /_cluster/health
        String response = transport.execute("GET", "/_cluster/health", null);
        System.out.println("Cluster health: " + response);
    }
}
```

When the `build()` method is called, the builder creates a fully‑configured
`HttpTransport` instance that can be reused for any number of HTTP API calls
against the Elasticsearch cluster.

---

## 4. Summary of Requirements Fulfilled

| Requirement | Implementation |
|-------------|----------------|
| **Proxy with optional username/password** | `proxyHost`, `proxyPort`, `proxyCredentials()`; passed to `HttpClient` as a `Proxy` and `ProxyAuthenticator`. |
| **Disable proxy, including system proxies** | `useSystemProxy(false)` sets `Proxy.NO_PROXY`; otherwise the builder respects the JVM defaults. |
| **Client credentials** | `credentials(username,password)` stored and added as `Authorization: Basic …` on every request. |
| **Certificate verification** | `disableSslVerification()` flips `sslVerify`; the transport disables host verification when `false`. |
| **Add HTTP headers to all requests** | `defaultHeader(name,value)` and `defaultHeaders(map)` populate a map that is merged into the `HttpClient` and the request builder. |
| **Global timeout** | `timeout(Duration)` configures both the client’s connect timeout and the request timeout. |
| **`build()` method** | Returns a new `Transport` (`HttpTransport`) with all configured settings applied. |

Feel free to adapt the concrete `Transport` implementation to the HTTP client library of your choice – the builder contract stays exactly the same. Happy coding!

