## 3. How to Compile & Link

Assuming you have a standard CUDA toolchain and the MAPS‑Multi headers installed:

```bash
# 1) Compile the kernel + host helper into a shared object
nvcc -c -arch=sm_70 -Xcompiler -fPIC gol_update.cu -o gol_update.o

# 2) Link with MAPS‑Multi (replace <path> with your installation)
g++ -shared -o libgol_maps.so gol_update.o \
    -I<path>/maps_multi/include \
    -L<path>/maps_multi/lib -lmaps_multi -lcudart

# 3) In your Python test script (or C++ harness) load the library:
#    import ctypes
#    lib = ctypes.CDLL('./libgol_maps.so')
#    lib.gol_update_test_case.argtypes = [ctypes.c_char_p,
#                                         ctypes.c_size_t,
#                                         ctypes.c_size_t,
#                                         ctypes.c_uint8]
#    lib.gol_update_test_case.restype = None
```

The function `gol_update_test_case` can now be called from any MAPS‑Multi test description, e.g.:

```python
# Python pseudo‑code (MAPS‑Multi test description)
def gol_life_test():
    lib.gol_update_test_case(b"gol_glider", rows=128, cols=128, init_pattern=0)
    # The framework will compare the result with a reference image.
    # If they differ, it will automatically invoke the PNG‑save routine.
```

